+---
+aliases:
+  - unified observability stack (metrics, logs, traces, alerts, dashboards)
+status: idea
+created: 2026-05-16
+---
+# Spec [[cat004]] [[cat003]] [[board]]
+
+## problem
+
+Acme's three services (`auth`, `metrics`, `reports`) currently observe themselves through three uncoordinated mechanisms: stdout for application logs, an ad-hoc Prometheus scraper bolted into the `metrics` service, and no distributed tracing at all. Alerts are printed to stdout and read by no one. There is no shared library for any of this — every service reinvents whatever it needs at the moment.
+
+The ask is a unified observability story for the platform, replacing the current mess with reusable horizontal capabilities. Because the ask packs five distinct observability concerns into "one feature," and the `ft###` schema is single-`providing` / single-`api_surface` / single-`status`, this proposal will mint **five separate Features** at spec-writing time, not one monolithic "observability" feature:
+
+- **`ft###` candidate 1 — metrics-emission.** Shared client for declaring counters / gauges / histograms and exposing a Prometheus scrape endpoint per service. Consumers: all three services. Replaces the ad-hoc scraper currently embedded in the `metrics` service. `api_surface` is the metric-declaration API (`Counter("foo_total").inc()`).
+- **`ft###` candidate 2 — structured-logging.** JSON log formatter with levels, correlation-id propagation, and a uniform schema. Consumers: all three services. Replaces stdout `print` calls. `api_surface` is a `get_logger(__name__)` factory returning a configured logger.
+- **`ft###` candidate 3 — distributed-tracing.** OpenTelemetry SDK wrapper that emits spans, propagates trace-ids across in-process and HTTP boundaries, and exports to a collector. Consumers: all three services. New capability — nothing replaces. `api_surface` is span-start / span-attribute helpers (`with tracer.start_span("name"):`).
+- **`ft###` candidate 4 — alerting-rules.** Alert-rule authoring contract (where rules live, how they bind to metrics, how they fire), plus a router that delivers fired alerts to a target channel. Consumers: every service that wants to be alerted on. Replaces "alerts via stdout" from the `metrics` service. `api_surface` is the rule YAML schema + the configured router endpoint.
+- **`ft###` candidate 5 — dashboards.** Dashboard-as-code provisioning so each service can register its panels. Consumers: every service. New capability. `api_surface` is the dashboard JSON schema + the provisioning command.
+
+Each of the five has its own `## providing`, its own `## api_surface`, its own consumer ergonomics, and could plausibly carry its own lifecycle — that is the granularity test the skill enforces, and these five each pass it. They are not one feature.
+
+**Sizing call — one `sp###`, not five.** The skill's default is one `sp###` unless per-feature work is independent and non-trivial in a way that demands separate board lifecycles. Reading against the rule, the per-feature work is non-trivial, but:
+
+1. The user explicitly framed this as a unified roll-out replacing today's mess, not five independent product bets.
+2. No backlog story is currently blocked on any one of the five — there is no urgency that would make ship-time skew (tracing in Q3 vs alerting in Q1) more valuable than a coherent design pass.
+3. Two of the five (dashboards, alerting) functionally depend on the metrics pipeline shipping first, so a single coherent plan keeps the sequencing legible.
+4. The skill explicitly says "merging later is harder than splitting later" — splitting at task level during `spec-refinement` is cheap; reuniting five independent specs after the fact is not.
+
+The single `sp001` will list all five `ft###` candidates in `## solution` at spec-writing, then break into per-feature tasks at `spec-refinement`. If during refinement any one of the five turns out large enough to warrant its own board lifecycle, it can be peeled off into its own `sp###` then — at task granularity that decision is cheap.
+
+**Consumers (concrete).** All three services consume all five features. No feature has only one consumer.
+
+**Migration intent.** Two ad-hoc sites get replaced rather than augmented:
+
+- The Prometheus scraper currently embedded in `src/services/metrics/` migrates to consume `ft###` metrics-emission like every other service. The `metrics` service stops being the metrics-collection special-case and becomes a normal consumer.
+- The stdout alert path in `src/services/metrics/` gets routed through `ft###` alerting-rules.
+
+No existing `im###` card describes these ad-hoc sites today (im001 is the reports dashboard only), so the migration writeups will land at spec-writing alongside the new feature drafts. Once those ad-hoc sites are removed, the platform has a single observability story.
+
+**Binding ADRs.** None yet in `[[cat004]]`. Decisions that will likely fall out of design (collector backend choice, retention windows for traces and logs, alert routing target) should be filed as ADRs during `spec-writing`. `[[adr0003]]` (no SMTP relay — services use smtplib directly) sits in `[[cat003]]` and is adjacent; it constrains how alerts can be delivered today (direct smtplib only), which the alerting-rules feature will need to either inherit or supersede.
+
+**Categories.** `[[cat004]]` (observability) is the primary home. `[[cat003]]` (infrastructure) appears in the H1 because alerting routing and dashboard provisioning are deployment / cross-service plumbing concerns.
+
+---
+
+Index: [[board]]
